December 13, 2015

Background

In this script, we apply the Normal Topic Model (NTM) on mixture of sinusoidally varying gene expression data matrix with and without wavelet transformation. The idea is to replicate patterns similar to sparse factor analysis, but to focus more on clustering the samples based on the expression patterns.

source('../R/ntmfit.R')

Toy example (mixture of sinusoid data matrix)

We simulate two sets of sinusoidal expression for \(100\) genes over \(256\) time points in order and then mix them with a mixing proportion of \(0.5\). For the first set of sinusoidal expression, the amplitudes for all the genes are \(10\), the phases for the first \(50\) genes are \(2\) and that of the last \(50\) genes being \(5\). The error variation besides the signal for each genes is taken to be generated from \(\chi^2_{4}\) distribution. For the second set of sinusoidal expression, the amplitudes for all the genes are \(5\), the phases for the first \(50\) genes are \(3\) and that of the last \(50\) genes being \(2\). The error variation besides the signal for each genes is taken to be generated from \(\chi^2_{1}\) distribution.

library(PMA)
## Loading required package: plyr
## Loading required package: impute
library(cellcycleR)
library(wavethresh)
## Loading required package: MASS
## WaveThresh: R wavelet software, release 4.6.6, installed
## 
## Copyright Guy Nason and others 1993-2013
## 
## Note: nlevels has been renamed to nlevelsWT
G <- 100;
num_cells <- 256;
amp_genes1 <- rep(10, G);
phi_genes1 <- rep(c(2,5), each=G/2);
sigma_genes1 <- rchisq(G, 4);
cell_times_sim <- sort(sample(seq(0,2*pi, 2*pi/(num_cells-1)), num_cells, replace=FALSE));
cycle_data1 <- t(sim_sinusoidal_cycle(G, amp_genes1, phi_genes1, sigma_genes1, cell_times_sim));
amp_genes2 <- rep(5, G);
phi_genes2 <- rep(c(3,2), each=G/2);
sigma_genes2 <- rchisq(G, 1);
cycle_data2 <- t(sim_sinusoidal_cycle(G, amp_genes2, phi_genes2, sigma_genes2, cell_times_sim));
cycle_data <- 0.5*cycle_data1 + 0.5*cycle_data2;

Example plots of two samples from the two groups in the example described above.

plot(cycle_data1[2,], type="l");

plot(cycle_data1[(2+G/2),], type="l")

plot(cycle_data2[2,], type="l");

plot(cycle_data2[(2+G/2),], type="l")

plot(cycle_data[2,], type="l");

plot(cycle_data[(2+G/2),], type="l")

Applying Normal Topic Model

Next, we apply the NTMfit() function on the this data.

system.time(out1 <- NTMfit(cycle_data, K=2));
##    user  system elapsed 
##   2.607   0.011   2.633

We plot the Structure plot for the topic proportions obtained from the model fit.

K <- 2;
barplot(t(out1$omega_out),col=2:(K+1),axisnames=F,space=0,border=NA,main="",las=1,ylim=c(0,1),cex.axis=1.5,cex.main=1.4)
title(main=paste("Structure Plot topic proportions,k=",K))

plot(out1$alpha_out[1,], type="l")

plot(out1$alpha_out[2,], type="l")

Wavelet Transformation of data matrix

wave_data <- t(apply(cycle_data, 1, function(x)
                                  {
                                      out <- wd(x, filter.number = 3, family = "DaubExPhase")
                                      return(out$D)
                                  }));

Applying Normal Topic Model on wavelet transformed data

Now apply NTMfit() function on the this wavelet-transformed data.

system.time(out2 <- NTMfit(wave_data, K=2));
##    user  system elapsed 
##   2.618   0.012   2.643

We plot the Structure plot for the topic proportions obtained from the above model fit.

K <- 2;
barplot(t(out2$omega_out),col=2:(K+1),axisnames=F,space=0,border=NA,main="",las=1,ylim=c(0,1),cex.axis=1.5,cex.main=1.4)
title(main=paste("Structure Plot topic proportions,k=",K))

Recreating back factors from wavelet transform

Reforming the cluster patterns by reverse transforming the alpha output from the NTMfit() model fit above.

W <- GenW(n=num_cells, filter.number=3, family="DaubExPhase")
idwt <- W[,-1] %*% t(out2$alpha_out);
plot(idwt[,1], type="l")

plot(idwt[,2], type="l")

The NTM (Normal Topic model) does a pretty decent job at clustering the two groups of sinusoidal wave patterns both without and with wavelet transforms.
